<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the Welsh Liberal Democrats (DWB 13)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the Welsh Liberal Democrats (DWB 13)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Welsh Liberal Democrats welcome the majority of the UK Government’s announcements on the Silk Commission and are satisfied with their provision in the draft Wales Bill.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The draft Wales Bill and Silk Commission are a unique opportunity to shape democracy in Wales. We must ensure that the Welsh and UK Governments and legislatures take this opportunity, and do not let progress pass them by.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Welsh Liberal Democrats believe that power and authority derive and flow upwards from the people and that power must be exercised at the most appropriate local level. We are the historic party of federalism and home rule, and have long supported a federal system as part of our vision for the UK’s constitutional future.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Welsh Liberal Democrats welcome the UK Government’s offer of devolving income tax on the same basis as that legislated for in the Scotland Act 2012. While not our preferred method of devolving income tax, we welcome this as a major step forward in the devolution settlement and are keen to see swift progress on the referendum. We would recommend that the Welsh Affairs Committee monitors the referendum’s progress and works with the UK Government to ensure a smooth process.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We welcome the UK Government’s support for Stamp Duty Land Tax (SDLT), landfill tax, business rates and their provision in the draft Wales Bill.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would encourage the Welsh Affairs Committee to work with the UK Government to ensure that investigations progress into the feasibility of devolving the aggregates levy.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We welcome the changes in electoral arrangements that provide for a move to five year fixed terms; restore dual candidacy; and ensure that Assembly Members cannot be MPs at the same time.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would recommend that if scrutiny of the draft Wales Bill goes well then the actual Bill should be commenced in this session of Parliament.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_Toc377477727"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Welsh Liberal Democrats are the state party of the Liberal Democrats in Wales. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are very glad that the Government in Westminster established the independent Commission on Devolution in Wales (the ‘Silk’ Commission) to review the present financial and constitutional arrangements in Wales. The Welsh Liberal Democrats are represented on the Commission by Rob Humphries, Director of the Open University in Wales. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We welcome the Prime Minister and Deputy Prime Minister’s announcement on November 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2013 in Cardiff that the UK Government accepts the majority of the Silk Commission’s recommendations. The draft Wales Bill will place into law the majority of the Silk Commission’s recommendations for fiscal powers. We have regularly supported reforms to increase the responsibility that Welsh ministers have over the money they spend, but also to ensure that they have the right legal and financial powers to deliver a wide range of solutions to the challenges Wales faces, particularly in order to stimulate the Welsh economy.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Liberal Democrats, in Wales and across the UK, believe that power and authority derive and flow upwards from the people and that power must be exercised at the most appropriate local level. We have long supported a federal system as part of our vision for the UK’s constitutional future. The Silk Commission and draft Wales Bill present a unique opportunity to strengthen this framework as far as Wales in concerned.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are submitting this evidence for your consideration in order to voice our views on the draft Wales Bill. While generally supportive, we are keen to see swift progress on this legislation. We would recommend that if scrutiny of the draft Wales Bill goes well then the actual Bill should be commenced in this session of Parliament.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_Toc377477728"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Devolution of taxation and borrowing powers</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_Toc377477729"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Partial devolution of income tax, and full devolution of stamp duty land tax, landfill tax, business rates and other smaller taxes to the National Assembly for Wales and Welsh Government.</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Welsh Liberal Democrats welcomed the Silk Commission’s recommendation that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">income tax should be devolved to the Assembly, subject to a referendum, and that 10p should be deducted from each of the main UK rates in Wales, with the Welsh Government able to set to vary the basic, higher and additional rates of tax independently.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We were pleased to see the UK Government’s offer of devolving income tax on the same basis as that legislated for in the Scotland Act 2012. While not our preferred </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">method of devolving income tax, we welcome this as a major step forward in the devolution settlement for Wales. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sharing the income tax base between Westminster and Cardiff Bay would significantly enhance the accountability of the National Assembly and the Welsh Government, as income tax contributes the greatest proportion of tax revenue in Wales and would provide a relatively stable revenue stream. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We welcome the Government’s agreement with the Silk Commission that SDLT, landfill tax, business rates and other smaller taxes would be devolved to the National Assembly for Wales and the Welsh Government. We also welcome the UK Government’s announcement that the Assembly should be given the power to introduce specified taxes, subject to agreement of the UK Government.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The devolution of SDLT could enable the National Assembly to address the acute housing crisis in Wales, by helping to lower the cost of developing and buying houses in Wales. The property market in Wales has distinct characteristics from elsewhere in the UK and devolution of SDLT would help Welsh Government policy better reflect this. The Welsh Government response to the UK Government consultation on devolving SDLT claims that ‘a devolved and reformed tax’ could ‘have the potential to promote jobs and economic growth in a way that would benefit both Wales and the wider UK’. Devolution of landfill tax will provide an excellent lever in a policy area largely devolved to the National Assembly. Greater control over business rates beyond the multiplier would allow the Welsh government to deliver a more coherent reform of business rates and encourage business investment. These taxes will greatly help to stimulate the Welsh economy, and we welcome their devolution.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK Government has said it will keep the devolution of aggregates levy under review, with the intention of devolving in the future subject to the resolution of on-going state aid issues and negotiations at an EU level.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given that waste management and recycling are largely devolved to the National Assembly, and landfill tax is to be devolved as well, we would support the devolution of aggregates levy to the National Assembly if on-going state aid issues can be resolved. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would encourage the Welsh Affairs Committee to work with the UK Government to ensure that investigations into resolving this area progress.</span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><a name="_Toc377477730"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The power for the National Assembly for Wales to be able to trigger a referendum on the devolution of income tax;</span></a></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Welsh Liberal Democrats believe that the people of Wales should be able to decide whether the Welsh Government and National Assembly should have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">responsibility for an element of income tax. We believe that the National Assembly for Wales is the right body to be able to trigger a referendum on the devolution of income tax and is provided for in the draft Wales Bill.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Welsh Liberal Democrats support and hope for progress to be made in this area soon. We will be campaigning firstly for a referendum to be held and then for a positive outcome in that referendum.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would hope that the UK Government and the Welsh Government will work together to ensure that triggering and holding the referendum is a smooth process and progresses as soon as is feasible following the passage of the Wales Bill.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would recommend that the Welsh Affairs Committee work with the UK Government to ensure the smooth passage of the Wales Bill.</span></p><h2 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><a name="_Toc377477731"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Increased capital borrowing powers for the Welsh Government.</span></a><br /><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Silk Commission said that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to be fully accountable for its spending decisions The Welsh Government should be able to influence the total of its capital spending in any one year as well. The Silk Commission recommended the Welsh Government has the capacity to borrow for capital investment on a prudent basis subject to limits agreed with HM Treasury. In addition, the Welsh Government should be given similar powers to the Scottish Government over borrowing for current spending to manage the volatility of tax receipts under the new funding system.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In our submission to the Silk Commission, we asked for borrowing powers equivalent to those proposed for the Scottish Parliament – capital borrowing limit of 10% of the total capital budget each year, with a cap at around 10 times this. We also asked for a very small amount of revenue borrowing. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK Government has accepted in principle the case for devolving borrowing powers, but the precise levels of capital borrowing will depend on the outcome of the income tax referendum. The UK Government will provide the Welsh Government with early access to limited capital borrowing powers in advance of the implementation of tax powers in order to begin projects such as the M4 development in South Wales. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Welsh Liberal Democrats welcome these borrowing powers as a way to provide the Welsh Government with more scope to stimulate the economy with investment in significant capital expenditure projects.</span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><a name="_Toc377477732"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></a></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">National Assembly for Wales electoral arrangements</span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><a name="_Toc377477733"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Move the National Assembly for Wales from four to five year fixed terms;</span></a></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We supported extending the length of the current (fourth) Assembly to avoid an election clash in 2015. Now that the Westminster elections will be every five years, we support extending Assembly terms to five years in order to avoid future clashes.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This will help ensure that Assembly issues receive the hearing they deserve during election campaigns. Some confusion exists over which powers are held by Westminster and which are held by the National Assembly. Research by the Wales Governance Centre suggests people’s perception of how far devolution has gone depends on how far they would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">like</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> devolution to go.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> These findings may reflect the lack of clarity in the Welsh devolution settlement. Maintaining a separation between the two cycles of electoral campaigns would help ensure that clarity between the responsibilities of the two institutions and their impact on Wales is improved. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst not the most common, five year terms are found across the world for other national legislatures. We support a five-year fixed term, to complement the introduction of five-year fixed-term parliaments by the UK government. </span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><a name="_Toc377477734"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Restore the right for candidates to stand on both a constituency and regional list during Assembly elections;</span></a></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We support the removal of the ban on dual candidacy. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The ban was introduced in 2006 as the then UK Government felt losing constituency candidates becoming regional Assembly Members “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">devalues the integrity of the electoral system in the eyes of the public and acts as a disincentive to vote in constituency elections.” </span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In reality it has reduced voter choice and undermined the credibility of the electoral system by punishing parties for success. The argument that turnout would diminish as voters would be unprepared to vote in elections where some losing constituency candidates were likely to be elected as regional candidates has been proven to be unfounded and it is accepted in Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the London Assembly. </span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><a name="_Toc377477735"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ensure Assembly Members cannot be MPs at the same time.</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">No-one should be able to serve as an AM and an MP concurrently. This prohibition currently exists for the European Parliament</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Being an AM, MP or MEP should be a full-time job and should not be undertaken alongside a comparable full-time role.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consequently, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e support the introduction of ban on dual mandates.</span></p><h2 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><a name="_Toc377477736"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary and Recommendations</span></a></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Welsh Liberal Democrats welcome the majority of the UK Government’s announcements on recommendations of the Silk Commission Part I. They present a historic opportunity for Wales and Welsh democracy.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While generally supportive of the draft Wales Bill, we are keen to see swift progress on this legislation. We would recommend that if scrutiny of the draft Wales Bill goes well then the actual Bill should be commenced in this session of Parliament.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would recommend that the Welsh Affairs Committee work with the UK Government to ensure the smooth passage of the Wales Bill.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would recommend that the Welsh Affairs Committee work with the UK Government to ensure the smooth passage of the referendum on income tax powers.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would encourage the Welsh Affairs Committee to work with the UK Government to ensure that investigations into resolving state aid issues around the aggregates </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">levy area progress.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">16 January 2014</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right; text-indent:72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.clickonwales.org/2013/11/polls-suggest-were-a-land-of-wishful-thinking/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.clickonwales.org/2013/11/polls-suggest-were-a-land-of-wishful-thinking/</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> UK Government White Paper on Better Governance for Wales (2005), pp.28-9</span></p></body></html>